If you are fine with a slight compromise, then this is very easy to do in Java. Rather than put the button inside of the text field, just make it *look* like the button is inside of the text field. If you are fine with that, here is what you can do.

```java

   private JPanel createContent()
   {
   
      final JPanel panel = new JPanel();
      panel.setBackground(Color.BLACK);
      panel.setBorder(BorderFactory.createLineBorder(Color.YELLOW));
   
      final JTextField textField = new JTextField();
      textField.setBackground(Color.BLACK);
      textField.setForeground(Color.WHITE);
      textField.setText(&quot;Enter your license key&quot;);
      textField.setBorder(BorderFactory.createLineBorder(Color.BLACK));
      textField.addMouseListener(
         new MouseAdapter()
         {
         
            public void mouseClicked(MouseEvent event)
            {
            
               textField.selectAll();
            
            }
         
         });
      
      final JButton button = new JButton();
      button.setBackground(Color.YELLOW);
      button.setForeground(Color.WHITE);
      button.setText(&quot;Connect&quot;);
      
      panel.add(textField);
      panel.add(button);
      
      return panel;
      
   }

```

In the above method, I create a panel, set its background to black, and give it a yellow border. By doing this, I am making that yellow border simulate the border of the text field.

Next, I add my text field to the panel, and remove all decorations that would make the user think that the text field is smaller than the yellow border than above. That means having a black border on a black background.

Finally, I add the button to the panel, then return it.

Here is a complete example.

```java

